Body:
## The setup

The translator declares every local-flavored built-in (`UV`, `COLOR`, `TIME`, `MODULATE`, `SCREEN_UV`, `TEXTURE_PIXEL_SIZE`, `SCREEN_PIXEL_SIZE`) as **local variables at the top of `main()`**. So inside `fragment()`, your code can read and write them naturally — they're just locals.

```glsl
shader_type canvas_item;
void fragment() {
    COLOR = vec4(UV.x, UV.y, 0.0, 1.0);  // works fine
}
```

## The gotcha

If you define a helper function — even a small one — it's emitted at the **top level** of the GLSL, outside `main()`. It doesn't see main's locals:

```glsl
shader_type canvas_item;

vec3 stripes() {
    return vec3(step(0.5, fract(UV.y * 10.0)));  // ❌ UV undefined here
}

void fragment() {
    COLOR = vec4(stripes(), 1.0);
}
```

WebGL rejects this with `'UV' : undeclared identifier`. The translator passes the source through without rewriting — `UV` is a local in `main()`, not a global, so `stripes()` can't reach it.

## The workaround

Pass built-ins as parameters. It's idiomatic GLSL anyway — keeps helpers pure and reusable.

```glsl
shader_type canvas_item;

vec3 stripes(vec2 uv) {
    return vec3(step(0.5, fract(uv.y * 10.0)));
}

void fragment() {
    COLOR = vec4(stripes(UV), 1.0);
}
```

Same pattern for the others — pass `TIME`, `COLOR`, etc. through as parameters wherever a helper needs them. `inout vec4` works if you want the helper to mutate `COLOR`:

```glsl
void apply_tint(inout vec4 color, vec3 tint) {
    color.rgb *= tint;
}

void fragment() {
    apply_tint(COLOR, vec3(1.0, 0.5, 0.5));
}
```

## Why we didn't auto-inject parameters

Two paths considered:

1. **Inline helpers into main()** — substantively rewriting the source. Means the translator needs a real recursive-descent parser to find function bodies, identify which helpers reference which built-ins, and inline them at call sites. ~10x the parser code for one gotcha.
2. **Wrap built-ins in a global struct or pass through a calling convention** — every helper would need an injected first parameter holding all built-ins. Workable but adds magic that doesn't match what Godot or GLSL actually does, and makes error messages weird ("why is this `bf_builtins.UV` thing in my error log?").

The "pass UV as a parameter" pattern is what idiomatic GLSL does anyway, and Godot's own shader compiler has the same constraint (the runtime injects built-ins as locals into `fragment()`'s scope; helpers don't see them). Matching that behavior keeps the mental model 1:1 with Godot.

> tip: if you're writing a lot of helpers that all need the same built-ins, consider defining one helper that takes everything as parameters and have it call the others. Keeps the parameter list at the call sites short.
